		<div id="post_message_1379672"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Alikat Astrae</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1379506#post1379506" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Wow, put me on the spot why don't you.  OK, stood my ground to stop a very large horse that was dragging its rider.  Pulled a couple of idiots out of surf I wouldn't swim in for a million dollars.  Stood over my best friend with my knife in my hand for hours until she recovered from the shit they slipped her, wondering what their next move was going to be.  I think those are reasonable examples.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Sorry, Ali - I figured it was fair game since you'd brought it up first.  <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Wink" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Anyway, with all due respect (and those really were some very courageous acts), I'm not really sure that any of those situations counts as &quot;far more dangerous&quot; than the situation in the article.  They were all dangerous, yes - but entering close-quarter, unarmed, one-on-one combat (in a bus aisle, it's one-on-one - any additional combatants are only going to be able to shove you in the back) with an armed psychopath?  That's kinda way up there on the &quot;dangerous recreational activities&quot; list.  I can agree to disagree if your assessment is different.  <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
<br />
In any case - as Fnag pointed out, in all of your examples there was something to gain by stepping in.  In this case, what would have been gained by subduing the attacker?  The kid was mortally wounded (based on Caton's quotes, he died before the bus was even empty), and nobody knew (at that point) that the attacker would start violating his corpse.  Even if they had known that - and I hate to sound crass here - but I can't think of a rationale that could justify putting their own lives in jeopardy to protect the dignity of a stranger's corpse, particularly when they're un-armed and an armed response is already on the way.<br />
<br />
Now, had he turned and started menacing other passengers and preventing them from leaving the bus (i.e. if it had been a situation where it was &quot;him or us&quot;), I suspect you'd have seen a much different reaction.  <br />
<br />
<br />
@Pyron:  Your ignorance is astounding.  I suggest you read up a little more on the Homolka/Bernardo case.  You seem to be missing most of the facts.<br />
<br />
Here's a start for you: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karla_Homolka" target="_blank">Wiki article</a>.</div>
