			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Re: Cowards</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#D1D1E1; background-color:#D1D1E1" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1379690"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Pyron</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1379682#post1379682" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Well, for one thing the state didn't have to let her stay anonymous after she was out.  She also could have been institutionalized.  She could have been locked up for her own protection, etc.  There are plenty of ways she could have been dealt with.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>So - you're advocating vigilante justice, then?  Publicize her whereabouts and let someone on the outside kill her?  <br />
<br />
Or perhaps advocating an abuse of the &quot;mental disorder&quot; standard to institutionalize her?  She's not crazy - she's evil.  Evil is not a mental disorder.<br />
<br />
Locked up for her own protection?  Awesome solution - but Canada doesn't have a facility in Cuba where people can be held indefinitely, without legal recourse.  I think, lacking such a facility, her lawyer would get her released pretty quickly.<br />
<br />
If you want to criticize the Canadian justice system, go right ahead - but please have some sort of alternative solution, something concrete that you would have done in the same situation.  Preferably something that falls within the legal system - hell, falls within ANY legal system, Canadian or American.  <br />
<br />
<br />
FYI, Canada does have a &quot;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dangerous_offender" target="_blank">Dangerous Offender</a>&quot; designation, which can be (and is) used to keep offenders incarcerated beyond the terms of their sentence. It does not require that the offender be suffering from a mental disorder - it only requires that they be too dangerous to be released into society. Homolka's husband, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Bernardo" target="_blank">Paul Bernardo</a> was declared a Dangerous Offender for those crimes, and is unlikely to ever be released.  <br />
<br />
Homolka was not designated a Dangerous Offender because the evidence of her involvement was never able to be introduced against her - as such, it could not be used as a factor in whether to apply that designation to her.<br />
<br />
<br />
It's easy to criticize something when you don't know all the facts.  So now that you're more informed, please enlighten us - what would you have done differently?  Or might you concede that, yeah it's a moral outrage that she has her freedom, but that this was the best (legal) outcome available.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		
