	</table>
</div>Honestly, I think the vigilante solution is the best solution in this case.  There's an old saw that hard cases make poor law, and I agree with that.  However, that also implies that sometimes the law is not the best way to deal with an exceptional situation .<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Zarbonius</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1379690#post1379690" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">FYI, Canada does have a &quot;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dangerous_offender" target="_blank">Dangerous Offender</a>&quot; designation, which can be (and is) used to keep offenders incarcerated beyond the terms of their sentence. It does not require that the offender be suffering from a mental disorder - it only requires that they be too dangerous to be released into society. Homolka's husband, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Bernardo" target="_blank">Paul Bernardo</a> was declared a Dangerous Offender for those crimes, and is unlikely to ever be released.  <br />
<br />
Homolka was not designated a Dangerous Offender because the evidence of her involvement was never able to be introduced against her - as such, it could not be used as a factor in whether to apply that designation to her.<br />
<br />
<br />
It's easy to criticize something when you don't know all the facts.  So now that you're more informed, please enlighten us - what would you have done differently?  Or might you concede that, yeah it's a moral outrage that she has her freedom, but that this was the best (legal) outcome available.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>The fact that ANY evidence can be excluded is something that is broken in both the U.S. and the Canadian system.  The easiest way to fix that is to remove all exclusions and allow all available evidence to be heard.  That removes the whole problem with classifying her as a Dangerous Offender.<br />
<br />
But really, while this may have been the best legal outcome, it is not the best outcome.  Law is a means to an end, it is not an end in itself.</div>
