</div>I take it you feel the same way about anyone who has been convicted, served their sentence, and then NOT been killed once released?  In any country, of course - no need to restrict this to Canada.<br />
<br />
Do you even have any criteria on which to base this &quot;they should die, even though they served their sentence&quot; pronouncement?  All Murderers (1st degree?  2nd degree?) should be killed once released?  Rapists? Drunk drivers?  Or is it just &quot;what Pyron (or insert &lt;random_citizen&gt;) says goes&quot;?<br />
<br />
There is a huge difference between what is the &quot;best&quot; outcome in your own mind, and what is the &quot;best&quot; outcome in terms of society's interests.  It may be morally repugnant that she has her freedom again - but is it truly better for society that an individual citizen commits murder to rectify the situation?  That random citizens start acting as unappointed judge, jury and executioner on the basis of their own determination of what would be &quot;justice&quot;?<br />
<br />
Do you truly think that's a better way to run a justice system?  Do you really think society as a whole would be better off under such a system?  Can you see that maybe the gains of such a system *might* be outweighed by its potential drawbacks?<br />
<br />
<br />
What's really odd is that on the one hand you advocate vigilante justice, and on the other you propose changes to evidence exclusion laws.  Both would seem to address the problem here - so why advocate for both when only one is necessary to rectify the issue?</div>
